2022 inflation: Layoffs and Employment¶

Project Proposal¶

1. Project Aims¶

1.1 Introduction¶

During the coronavirus pandemic, technology companies boosted hiring to keep up with rising customer demand. However the situation has changed in 2022 [1]. The global surge in energy and agricultural prices has impacted many industries. Using Singapore as an example, the precipitous rise in energy prices have a significant impact on Singapore’s manufacturing and transport services. For instance, a 92% increase in energy prices will result in cost increases of 6 percentage points for manufacturing and 13.2 percentage points for transportation services [2]. The consequential lay off of workers from industries due to this surge in price has negatively impacted many employees all across the globe in various industries, particularly Technology. I will be cross-checking this with my own set of data. I thus wanted to analyse and acquire data on the industry that most heavily impacted due to the rise in inflation, in the attempts of understanding the risks involved in joining sectors that are volatile during periods of economic crisis. Simultaneously, narrowing down to finding out the company that is affected the most in this turbulent cause of changes. Additionally, I will be acquiring dataset from LinkedIn, a popular platform primarily used for networking and career development in which I will extract findings based on the current prevailing sector in which employees can find employment, in the attempts of collating and efficiently understanding the trend and the bird’s eye view in terms of employability in this current period. I will be finding the general trend of layoffs and will eventually center on the availability of local career opportunities(Singapore) and the viable sectors that can be seeked out by the locals. To my knowledge no similar work has been done in acquiring a detailed dataset that clearly distinguishes the industry/sector and company that has been most affected in terms of layoffs and a dataset that establishes the trending industry/sector that one could seek out for.

1.2 Aims and objectives¶

I would be exploring the following in this project:

  • Analyse through sources Kaggle and Intellizence the degree of consequence of inflation on which industry/company this year(2022)?
    • Which industry is the most/least affected by this inflation?
    • Which company is the most affected by this inflation?
  • Analyse through Linked-In the job trends locally
    • Which sector is currently hiring the most?
    • Local career opportunities
  • Provide a summary and a comparison for relationships between different factor
    • The r/s between the top 5 industries and the layoffs from this industries*
    • The r/s between the industry that is hiring the most and the sectors that have high risk of layoffs

For my project proposal, my aims are to:

  • Extract data from three different types of dataset(Structured, semi-structured and unstructured) via websraping, data cleaning and visualisation
  • Gather data from the accumulated dataset on the number of layoffs in each industry.
  • Comparison of the collected data on the number of layoffs globally via exploratory data analysis to identify trends and anomalies
  • Comparison of the collected data from Linked-In on the types of jobs available
  • Consider the limitations of the source and the techniques used.

1.3 Data¶

1.3.1 Data requirements¶

Three datasets were chosen from the web pages, Intellizence [3], Kaggle [4] and Linked-In [5]. Intellizence, a semi-structured dataset, Kaggle, a structured dataset and Linked-In, an unstructured dataset. I chose these three datasets to establish and explain the style of extraction of three different types of dataset structures. Intellizence and Kaggle have 196 and 1732 layoffs listed respectively. Linked-In was chosen to extract data on the current industries that are still hiring. I will be extracting approximately 1000 jobs that are available of any chosen day in the year in Singapore. This is to provide a general view on the popular choice of hiring by companies/ industries.

I will be looking at the top 15 industries that have the highest layoffs so as to compare thoroughly the effect of the inflation. Following that, I will be finding out the top 15 jobs that are up for employment in Linked-In to find out which industry is still hiring, allowing me to craft out a possible solution for the layoffs.

1.3.2 Choice of source¶

I selected Intellizence and Kaggle as my source of data due to the relevancy and verifiability. Out of all the sources checked, Intellizence and Kaggle proved to be updated and relevant to the current trend on layoffs by different industries. On the other hand, Linked-In was chosen as, besides being one of the most popular job sites [6], it consented to webscraping.These three sources allows me to demonstrate the extraction of data from 3 different types of set, structured, semi-structured and unstructured. The following information below, gives a brief introduction on the source of data and the reason for the pick.

Kaggle(Structured data set)

  • A data collection site that contains huge repository of code and data.
  • Access to high quality data sets
  • Easily accessible

Intellizence(Semi-structured)

  • Signals-as-a-Service platform that provides accurate and useful intelligence
  • Monitors a variety of data sources that are 95% relevant.
  • Allowed webscraping

Linked-In(Unstructured)

  • One of the top job sites that has over 750 million users
  • Professional
  • Allowed webscraping

The Selennium library took approximately 20 minutes to load over 500 jobs into Jupyter notebook. Since I extracted 1000 jobs, it took about 40 minutes to add into the jupyter notebook.

1.3.3 Limitations and constraints of the data¶

1.3.3.1 Categories were subjective for different data sets¶

Both the sources Intellizence and Kaggle coined different companies under different categories in the industry section. For instance, Kaggle categorised some companies like Amazon under ‘Retail’ which in general is usually branded as a company under ‘Technology’. Cisco was categorised under ‘Infrastructure’ in Kaggle and ‘Technology’ in Intellizence. These changes in categorising the company in an industry causes confusion and misdirection for users as there is no standard categorisation of companies. Thus, it was difficult to ascertain which company or industry was affected by inflation the most. As such, I had to manually search up the name of the companies to check as to which industry they most generally fall into. This allowed me to finalise the industry that had the highest layoffs.

1.3.3.2 Both set of data had unequal number of layoffs listed¶

Kaggle and Intellizence had a drastic difference in the number of layoffs listed in their website. Kaggle had 1732 layoffs listed while Intellizence had a mere 196 layoffs listed. While both datas showed the highest layoff to be in the Technology industry, the unequal number of data on layoffs might give an inaccurate result. Since Intellizence only reported 196 layoffs, the information provided could be limited in understanding other type of information such as the least number of layoffs. This could also mean that other industries could potentially take the top spot in having the highest layoffs as the number of layoffs listed is so limited. This would mean that more datasets are needed in understanding and confirming whether the top industry is in fact technology.

1.4 Ethical considerations¶

1.4.1 Use of data sets¶

There is no prohibition against webscraping in the terms and conditions of any of the websites.

Consent to use content:

  • Intellizence terms and conditions stated that “customer should not intentionally or knowingly use the Services in a way that could harm Intellizence's ability to provide the Services by overloading, damaging, or otherwise interfering with that ability”.
  • Since no harm is done with the data set, I can safely assume that I am following the terms and conditions.
  • On the other hand, Kaggle’s terms and condition stated that “we can engage with third parties using the Services, but Kaggle has no control over such websites' content, accuracy, privacy policies or practices, or the viewpoints represented within. In addition, Kaggle will not and is unable to check, censor, or edit the content of any website or service operated by a third party. You release and hold us blameless from any and all liabilities resulting from your use of any third-party website or service by utilizing the Services.”
  • Since Kaggle is a website meant for the collection of datas, and we do not use the data for the wrong ideology, I can safely assume that I am following the terms and conditions.

1.4.4 Potential impacts of using layoff datas¶

Some data usage could have detrimental effects on people or organizations, such as the continuation of harmful and false assumptions or a reduction in revenue. Because of the following factors, I have determined that the risks associated with this project and how it will use the source data are minor. This research will concentrate on analyzing just the the layoffs of industries. The aforementioned limitations of the data used in this investigation have been mentioned. Throughout the study, limitations of the methodologies employed will be explored.

Webscraping¶

A CSV file containing a list of URLs needs to be analyzed for this project. Before importing the file and scraping the content of the URLs, a function should be defined to scrape the data as the URLs are iterated through. Each website has different HTML, so a separate function must be written to extract the necessary information from each one. Keep in mind that web scraping will take 5-10 minutes due to a website's requirement of a 10-second crawl delay. Scraping faster will result in being banned from the website.

soup = BeautifulSoup(url.content, 'html.parser')

df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Date', 'Company', 'Industry', 'Location', 'Layoff'])

#print(df)
for table in soup.find_all('table'):
       #print(table.get('class'))
    
     for row in table.tbody.find_all('tr'):    
    # Find all data for each column
         columns = row.find_all('td')

         if(columns != []):
                date = columns[0].text.strip()
                company = columns[1].text.strip()
                industry = columns[2].text.strip()
                location = columns[3].text.strip()
                jobs = columns[4].text.strip()
                datas=[date,company,industry,location,jobs]
                #print(datas)
                
                df = df.append({'Date': date,  'Company': company, 'Industry': industry,'Location': location,'Layoff': jobs},ignore_index=True)

Then it is selecting the top 10 rows of the sorted dataframe and creating a new dataframe 'topfocus' by taking only Location and Layoff Columns from the original dataframe 'data' and sorting by Layoff column.

This code is essentially finding the top 10 locations where the sum of Layoffs is the highest. It is useful for identifying the locations where layoffs are most concentrated and can be used for further analysis or decision making.

This code is using the Selenium webdriver to automate scrolling down the LinkedIn job search page and loading more job results, then it is extracting the company name, job title and location of the jobs.

  • i=2 and while i<=50: is used to scroll down the page 50 times, to load more job results on the page.

  • driver.execute_script("window.scrollTo(0, document.body.scrollHeight);") is used to scroll down the page

  • try: button = find_element(By.XPATH,'//button[@aria-label="Load more results"]').click() except: pass time.sleep(5) is used to click the "Load more results" button at the bottom of the page, if present

  • company_name, title_name and location_name are empty lists that will be used to store the extracted data.

  • try: is used to catch the exception when the end of the page is reached, and the loop is done

  • for j in range(num): company = driver.find_elements(By.CLASS_NAME, "base-search-card__subtitle")[j].text company_name.append(company) is used to extract the company names of the jobs and store them in the "company_name" list.

  • for i in range(num): title = driver.find_elements(By.CLASS_NAME, "base-search-card__title")[i].text title_name.append(title) is used to extract the job titles of the jobs and store them in the "title_name" list.

  • for k in range(num): location = driver.find_elements(By.CLASS_NAME, "job-search-card__location")[k].text location_name.append(location) is used to extract the locations of the jobs and store them in the "location_name" list.

  • except IndexError: print("Done") is used to catch the exception when the end of the page is reached, and the loop is done.

6.1 Summary¶

In conclusion, it is evident that the technology industry suffered a greater impact in comparison to the other industries during the inflation period in 2022, resulting in the large layoff of employees from the technological companies. The data sets from Kaggle and Intellizence clearly showed the relationships between the increase in layoffs and the industry that was impacted by it the most.

While the datasets allowed us to understand which industry was affected the most during the inflation period, it will be useful to explore more on how this can be overcome. While linked-in provides a short-term solution for lay-off employees to look into, it will be more useful and efficient to find out through other job sites as to what are the more popular jobs and industries employees can join instead of just one. On top of that, the limitations can also be looked into for a more compact analysis.
